trans-unit.source: Applies a filter to specified columns of a dataset
trans-unit.target: Applies a filter to specified columns of a dataset

trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>Apply Filter</ui> module to transform a column of numbers that typically represents some kind of audio or image signal), by applying a previously defined filter.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>Apply Filter</ui> module to transform a column of numbers that typically represents some kind of audio or image signal), by applying a previously defined filter.

trans-unit.source: Filters of this kind are used in digital signal processing to reduce noise or highlight a pattern.
trans-unit.target: Filters of this kind are used in digital signal processing to reduce noise or highlight a pattern.

trans-unit.source: The <ui>Apply Filter</ui> module returns a dataset that has been transformed by applying the filter.
trans-unit.target: The <ui>Apply Filter</ui> module returns a dataset that has been transformed by applying the filter.

trans-unit.source: Note that the module returns only the data in the columns that you specify by using the column selector.
trans-unit.target: Note that the module returns only the data in the columns that you specify by using the column selector.

trans-unit.source: If you want see other columns in the dataset, you must use the <link xlink:href="5714a225-befd-438a-9bb5-f6fdc50a4efb" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Add Columns</link> module after the filter.
trans-unit.target: If you want see other columns in the dataset, you must use the <link xlink:href="5714a225-befd-438a-9bb5-f6fdc50a4efb" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Add Columns</link> module after the filter.

trans-unit.source: Because the design of filters is separate from the process of applying a filter, filters are reusable.
trans-unit.target: Because the design of filters is separate from the process of applying a filter, filters are reusable.

trans-unit.source: For example, if you frequently work with data used for forecasting, you might design several types of moving average filters to train and compare multiple models.
trans-unit.target: For example, if you frequently work with data used for forecasting, you might design several types of moving average filters to train and compare multiple models.

trans-unit.source: For more information, see <link xlink:href="1889e4ca-7bf7-494d-b2cc-da9940468b9e" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Moving Average Filters</link>.
trans-unit.target: For more information, see <link xlink:href="1889e4ca-7bf7-494d-b2cc-da9940468b9e" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Moving Average Filters</link>.

trans-unit.source: After determining which type of filters work best for your data source, you can save the workflow to apply to other experiments or to different datasets.
trans-unit.target: After determining which type of filters work best for your data source, you can save the workflow to apply to other experiments or to different datasets.

trans-unit.source: Need to filter data from a dataset or remove missing values?
trans-unit.target: Need to filter data from a dataset or remove missing values?

trans-unit.source: Use this module to remove missing values or replace missing values with placeholders.
trans-unit.target: Use this module to remove missing values or replace missing values with placeholders.

trans-unit.source: Use this module to divide or filter your dataset by criteria such as a range of dates, a specific value, or regular expressions.
trans-unit.target: Use this module to divide or filter your dataset by criteria such as a range of dates, a specific value, or regular expressions.

trans-unit.source: Use this module to set a range and keep only the values within that range.
trans-unit.target: Use this module to set a range and keep only the values within that range.

trans-unit.source: A filter defined by using one of the following filter modules: <link xlink:href="11fbc6ba-3a9f-4492-b789-8ef8a9320306" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Threshold</link>, <link xlink:href="1889e4ca-7bf7-494d-b2cc-da9940468b9e" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">moving average</link>, <link xlink:href="a7974d98-616d-4a78-8966-cad384b41886" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">median</link>, <link xlink:href="1c22cafc-1da0-4dc5-9336-831ee3f2860b" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">IIR</link>, <link xlink:href="5bcfd02b-e359-4289-b75c-3aa9f3e4479f" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">FIR</link>, <link xlink:href="53f113fe-2e9d-45dd-a421-cdd7ada0567b" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">custom</link>.
trans-unit.target: A filter defined by using one of the following filter modules: <link xlink:href="11fbc6ba-3a9f-4492-b789-8ef8a9320306" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Threshold</link>, <link xlink:href="1889e4ca-7bf7-494d-b2cc-da9940468b9e" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">moving average</link>, <link xlink:href="a7974d98-616d-4a78-8966-cad384b41886" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">median</link>, <link xlink:href="1c22cafc-1da0-4dc5-9336-831ee3f2860b" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">IIR</link>, <link xlink:href="5bcfd02b-e359-4289-b75c-3aa9f3e4479f" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">FIR</link>, <link xlink:href="53f113fe-2e9d-45dd-a421-cdd7ada0567b" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">custom</link>.

trans-unit.source: A dataset that contains numeric values
trans-unit.target: A dataset that contains numeric values

trans-unit.source: When you have connected the dataset, you can select any numeric column, and the column’s values will be replaced with new values according to the predefined mathematical transformation.
trans-unit.target: When you have connected the dataset, you can select any numeric column, and the column’s values will be replaced with new values according to the predefined mathematical transformation.

trans-unit.source: Note that the original column values are still available in the dataset for reference, but the output of the filter is usually more useful for modeling.
trans-unit.target: Note that the original column values are still available in the dataset for reference, but the output of the filter is usually more useful for modeling.

trans-unit.source: With the <ui>Apply Filter</ui> module, you bind a specific filter to individual columns.
trans-unit.target: With the <ui>Apply Filter</ui> module, you bind a specific filter to individual columns.

trans-unit.source: If you need to apply different types of filters to different columns, you should use <ui>Project Columns</ui> to isolate the columns and apply different filter types in separate workflows.
trans-unit.target: If you need to apply different types of filters to different columns, you should use <ui>Project Columns</ui> to isolate the columns and apply different filter types in separate workflows.

trans-unit.source: The filters do not pass through data columns that are not affected by the filter.
trans-unit.target: The filters do not pass through data columns that are not affected by the filter.

trans-unit.source: That is, the output of <ui>Apply Filter</ui> contains only the transformed numeric values.
trans-unit.target: That is, the output of <ui>Apply Filter</ui> contains only the transformed numeric values.

trans-unit.source: However, you can use the <link xlink:href="5714a225-befd-438a-9bb5-f6fdc50a4efb" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Add Columns</link> module to join transformed values with the source dataset.
trans-unit.target: However, you can use the <link xlink:href="5714a225-befd-438a-9bb5-f6fdc50a4efb" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Add Columns</link> module to join transformed values with the source dataset.

trans-unit.target: The <externalLink><linkText>Filters</linkText><linkUri>http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=525732</linkUri></externalLink> sample demonstrates all filter types, using an engineered waveform dataset for illustration.

trans-unit.source: When you apply a filter to a column, note that the filter period is determined in part by the filter type, as follows:
trans-unit.target: When you apply a filter to a column, note that the filter period is determined in part by the filter type, as follows:

trans-unit.source: For finite impulse response (FIR), simple moving average, and triangular moving average filters, the filter period is <legacyBold>finite</legacyBold>.
trans-unit.target: For finite impulse response (FIR), simple moving average, and triangular moving average filters, the filter period is <legacyBold>finite</legacyBold>.

trans-unit.source: For infinite impulse response (IIR), exponential moving average, and cumulative moving average filters, the filter period is <legacyBold>infinite</legacyBold>.
trans-unit.target: For infinite impulse response (IIR), exponential moving average, and cumulative moving average filters, the filter period is <legacyBold>infinite</legacyBold>.

trans-unit.source: For threshold filters, the filter period is always <legacyBold>1</legacyBold>.
trans-unit.target: For threshold filters, the filter period is always <legacyBold>1</legacyBold>.

trans-unit.source: For median filters, regardless of the filter period, NaNs and missing values in the input signal do not produce new NaNs in output.
trans-unit.target: For median filters, regardless of the filter period, NaNs and missing values in the input signal do not produce new NaNs in output.

trans-unit.source: If a filter encounters a NaN or a missing value in the input dataset, the output dataset becomes spoiled with NaNs for some next number of samples, depending on the filter period.
trans-unit.target: If a filter encounters a NaN or a missing value in the input dataset, the output dataset becomes spoiled with NaNs for some next number of samples, depending on the filter period.

trans-unit.source: FIR, simple moving average, or triangular moving average filters have a finite period; thus, any missing value will be followed by a number of NaNs equal to the filter order minus one.
trans-unit.target: FIR, simple moving average, or triangular moving average filters have a finite period; thus, any missing value will be followed by a number of NaNs equal to the filter order minus one.

trans-unit.source: IIR, exponential moving average, or cumulative moving average filters have an infinite period; thus, after the first missing value is encountered, NaNs will continue to propagate indefinitely.
trans-unit.target: IIR, exponential moving average, or cumulative moving average filters have an infinite period; thus, after the first missing value is encountered, NaNs will continue to propagate indefinitely.

trans-unit.source: Because the period of a threshold filter equals 1, missing values and NaNs do not propagate.
trans-unit.target: Because the period of a threshold filter equals 1, missing values and NaNs do not propagate.

trans-unit.source: For median filters, NaNs and missing values encountered in the input dataset do not produce new NaNs in output, regardless of the filter period.
trans-unit.target: For median filters, NaNs and missing values encountered in the input dataset do not produce new NaNs in output, regardless of the filter period.
